elements.content: By changing ancillary tetradentate Schiff base ligands (L), two new one-dimensional azide-bridged manganese(III) coordination complexes [MnIII(L)(μ1,3-N3)] n [L = 5-Fsalen (1), 5-OCH3 (2); salen = N,N‘-bis(salicylidene)-1,2-diaminoethane] as well as a mononuclear complex [MnIII(salophen)(N3)] (3) [salophen = N,N‘-bis(salicylidene)-o-phenylenediamine] have been successfully obtained. All of them have been structurally and magnetically characterized. In the structures of 1 − 3 each MnIII ion is in a distorted octahedral geometry with an obvious Jahn−Teller effect, where the tetradentate L ligands all bind in the equatorial mode, whereas in the axial direction, the N3 - ion acts as an end-to-end bridge in 1 and 2 while a terminal group in 3 with a methanol molecule at the other end. Magnetic characterization shows that the μ1,3-bridging azide ion proves to mainly transmit antiferromagnetic interaction between MnIII ions, but these three complexes exhibit various magnetic behaviors at low temperatures. Noteworthily, complex 2 behaves as a weak ferromagnet with a relatively large coercive field of 2.3 kOe, much larger than the value reported previously.

Introduction

The design and synthesis of transition-metal coordination polymers bridged by small conjugated ligands, such as cyano, azido, oxalato, thiocyano, and nitrido, are currently under intense investigation in view of their structure diversity and in the context of molecule-based magnets. Among these short bridging ligands, in particular, the azide ion exhibits versatile bridging modes, such as μ-(1,3), μ-(1,1), and rare μ-(1,1,3), the latter two modes of which usually transfer ferromagnetic interactions between metal centers. To date, plenty of studies about the azide bridge have been dedicated to some divalent transition-metal coordination complexes (Cu2+, Co2+, Ni2+, Fe2+, Mn2+, etc.), possessing diverse structures from 1-D, 2-D, to 3-D supramolecular polymers with various magnetic properties. On the other hand, the MnIII ion itself has a high spin number and an obvious single-ion anisotropy, leading to intriguing molecule-based magnets,  especially for MnIII-containing single-molecule magnets or single-chain magnets. Also, manganese(III) coordination complexes were found to play important roles in the catalyst and biological field. However, trivalent manganese(III)-based coordination polymers bridged by the azide ion have been rarely reported.

elements.content: According to the literature on manganese(III), tetradentate Schiff bases (SBs) proved to be effective auxiliary ligands to stabilize the high oxidation state of manganese but usually led to low-dimensional MnIII compounds. Among those azide-bridged MnIII chains, [Mn(SB)(N3)] n , the azide bridge is inclined to adopt an end-to-end μ-(1,3) mode and pass antiferromagnetic interaction. Recently, another interesting azide-bridged MnIII complex, [Mn(5-Brsalen)(N3)] n , was reported with coexistence of spin canting and metamagnetism. Herein, by changing the side group of SB ligands, we obtained two new azide-bridged one-dimensional manganese(III) polymers, [MnIII(L)(μ1,3-N3)] n [L = 5-Fsalen (1), 5-OCH3 (2); salen = N,N‘-bis(salicylidene)-1,2-diaminoethane], as well as a mononuclear complex, [MnIII(salophen)(N3)] (3) [salophen = N,N‘-bis(salicylidene)-o-phenylenediamine], linked through extensive hydrogen-bond interactions into a two-dimensional supramolecular network. Magnetic studies show that these three complexes exhibit various magnetic behaviors at low temperatures. It is noteworthy that complex 2 behaves as a weak ferromagnet with a relatively large coercive field of 2.3 kOe, more than 10 times of that of the reported complex [Mn(5-Brsalen)(N3)] n , although they have very similar structures except for the side group of SBs.

elements.content: Crystal Structures of Complexes 1 − 3. Single-crystal X-ray analyses reveal that complexes 1 and 2 both consist of one-dimensional chains based on [MnIII(L)] subunits except for the side group of the Schiff base ligand. The ORTEP plot of complex 1 is shown in Figure a. There is only one crystallographically independent manganese(III) atom in a distorted octahedral geometry, which is coordinated by the N2O2 donor atoms from one 5-Fsalen ligand in the equatorial mode and two N donor atoms from two N3 - ions in the axial position. Each azide ligand functions as a trans-μ1,3 bridge to link monomeric [MnIII(5-Fsalen)]+ units into a one-dimensional ziazag chain along the c axis (Figure b), which belongs to Type I azide-bridged chain according to Prof. Escuer's classified method. In the equatorial plane the bond lengths of Mn(1)−O(1), Mn(1)−O(2), Mn(1)−N(1), and Mn(1)−N(2) are 1.875(2), 1.883(2), 1.976(2), and 1.986(2) Å, respectively, which are close to those in other MnIII−salen complexes. The O(1) and N(2) atoms are below the equatorial plane at 0.034 and 0.037 Å, the O(2) and N(1) atoms are above at 0.040 and 0.041 Å, and the centered MnIII ion is only above the plane at 0.01 Å. In comparison with the reported compound, [Mn(salen)N3], in complex 1 Mn(1), O(1), O(2), N(1), and N(2) are more coplanar. As expected, the bond lengths in the axial position of Mn(1)−N(3) and Mn(1)−N(5) (2.287(3) and 2.327(3) Å) are elongated due to a Jahn−Teller distortion at the high-spin d4 metal center; the bond angles of Mn(1)−N(3)−N(4) and Mn(1)−N(5)−N(4A) are 114.7(2)° and 118.5(2)°, respectively. These values are also similar to those in [Mn(salen)N3]. As for N3 - itself, N(3)−N(4) and N(4)−N(5A) have almost the same bond lengths (1.185(4) and 1.186(4) Å) and the N(3)−N(4)−N(5A) bond angle is 179.8(3)°, close to 180°, obviously different from the asymmetric NCNH- bridge in the similar MnIII polymers.

elements.content: Complex 1. The magnetic properties of complex 1 are shown in Figure . Figure a shows the temperature dependence of magnetic susceptibility from 1.9 to 300 K at a 1 kOe field. On cooling, the χm value increases slowly to a maximum value of 0.021 cm3 mol-1 at ca. 42.0 K, and then it has a small decrease to 0.017 cm3mol-1 at ca. 13.0 K, indicating the presence of an antiferromagnetic (AF) coupling. The following little anomaly around 10.0 K may be caused by a long-range antiferromagnetic ordering, which will be proved by the subsequent magnetism measurements. With the temperature further cooling down below 10.0 K, the χm value shows a sharp decrease again possibly due to the effect of zero-field splitting (ZFS) arising from the MnIII ion, the antiferromagnetic interaction between chains, and/or a field saturation effect. The data above 150 K obey the Curie−Weiss law (χm = C/(T − θ)) with C = 3.04 cm3 mol-1 K and θ = −69.7 K. The Curie constant is close to 3.0 cm3 mol-1 K as expected for one uncoupled spin-only MnIII ion, while the negative θ value confirms the dominant AF coupling between MnIII ions. Although this is at very low temperatures where some anisotropy may be significant, MnIII is expected to be Heisenberg-like in its magnetic properties. Fitting the data above 13 K using the model given by Weng and modified by Hiller with H = −2JS Mn S Mn gives the best fit parameters J = −4.4 cm-1, zJ ‘ = −1.4 cm-1 (z = 4), g = 2.016, and R = 1.4 × 10-4 {R = ∑[(χm)obs - (χm)calcd]2/∑(χm)obs 2} in which J and zJ ‘ represent the intrachain and interchain coupling constants between MnIII centers, respectively. These values prove an obvious AF coupling between not only intrachain MnIII ions but also interchain MnIII centers.

T N = 9.6 K, where the in-phase part χm‘ reaches a maximum and no obvious out-of-phase χm‘ ‘ reflection was found.

On cooling, the χm value keeps smoothly increasing and shows a broad peak at about 30 K, which reveals an overall antiferromagnetic coupling between MnIII ions in 2. The magnetic susceptibility above 100 K can be fit to the Curie−Weiss law; the Curie constant C value of 3.05 cm3 mol-1 K agrees very well with one independent high-spin MnIII ion, and the negative Weiss constant θ value of −51.1 K further confirms the strong antiferromagnetic coupling in 2. In contrast with 1, it seems that the intrachain coupling between MnIII ions in 2 is weaker while the interchain interaction is a bit stronger.

elements.content: Complex 3. The magnetic property of complex 3 is relatively simple in contrast with those of 1 and 2, as shown in Figure S4 (Supporting Information). From χm T versus T and versus T plots (Figure S4a) the χm T value at room temperature is 3.00 cm3 mol-1 K, in good accordance with the theoretical value for one spin-only high-spin MnIII ion. Upon cooling, the values of χm T keep decreasing in the 300−1.9 K range, indicating an overall antiferromagnetic coupling in 3. The magnetic susceptibility above 10 K can be well fit to the Curie−Weiss law with C = 3.02 cm3 mol-1 K, θ = −1.9 K. The Curie constant C value is also close to the expected value of 3.0 cm3 mol-1 K for one noninteracting MnIII ion (S = 2, g = 2), and the small negative θ value further confirms a possible very weak antiferromagnetic interaction in 3. The M versus H plot measured at 2.0 K (Figure S4b) shows that magnetization increases smoothly and reaches 2.94 Nβ mol-1, a bit smaller than the theoretical saturation value 4.0 Nβ mol-1 for one spin-only MnIII ion, confirming the weak antiferromagnetic interaction between MnIII ions again. Considering the long Mn···Mn distances in the structure of 3, we fit the data in a range of 2−300 K with the spin-only susceptibility model for a single MnIII ion19 and obtained the following best results:  zJ ‘ = −0.27 cm-1, g = 2.028, and R = 6.9 × 10-4, which also show the weak antiferromagneic interaction between the MnIII ions linked through hydrogen bonds.

elements.content: Similar to other azide-bridged MnIII complexes, these one-dimensional manganese(III) chains presented in this paper with long axial bonds should have only one dominant exchange pathway due to the small axial overlap, and it results in a weak antiferromagnetic interaction. The only magnetic orbital is the one derived from the MnIII dz 2 orbital, which may make a significant contribution to the coupling. The axial ligands will mainly provide a σ-type superexchange pathway with a mechanism involving the π orbitals of the bridging group being conceived. The weak ferromagnetism in 2 should arise from the spin canting of the antiferromagnetically interacted MnIII ions, and the origin of the spin canting should be mainly due to the asymmetric interactions between the neighboring MnIII ions in combination with possible local anisotropy of the MnIII ions.

elements.content: To date, with the efforts of some research groups as well as ours, a series of [Mn(salen)(N3)]-type complexes has been successfully obtained by changing the substituent group of the SBs (SBs = salen, 5-Fsalen, 5-Clsalen, 5-Brsalen, and 5-OCH3); some of their pertinent bond distances and angles and magnetic properties are listed in Table . We found that changing the side group of salen had little influence on the complex structures only with a subtle difference of the bond lengths and angles, which mainly consist of 1-D zigzag chains except for the special dinuclear cluster of the 5-Clsalen complex. On the other hand, they have obviously different magnetic properties at low temperatures with the change of the side group of salen, even though an overall antiferromagnetic coupling between manganese(III) ions was observed in these complexes. When salen has no side group, the corresponding complex displays no special phase transition at low temperatures, whereas when 5-Fsalen was used instead, the complex shows an antiferromagnetic ordering phase below 9.6 K. When salen was further replaced by 5-Brsalen, the combination of metamagnetism and weak ferromagnetism due to spin canting was first observed in the azide-bridged MnIII complexes, and then introduction of 5-OCH3 brought about an unprecedented hysteresis loop due to weak ferromagnetism. Noteworthy, the reported complex, [Mn(salpn)(N3)] n , has similar magnetic properties to that of [Mn(5-Fsalen)(N3)] n but different from that of [Mn(salen)(N3)] n . From Table it is found that the Mn−N−N angles in these azide-bridged MnIII chains are most obviously affected by the subtle structural change, which may be one of the reasons why they possess various magnetic properties.

Three new MnIII−Schiff base coordination complexes have been structurally and magnetically characterized in this paper. Structural analyses show that complexes 1 and 2consist of one-dimensional azide-bridged MnIII chains except for the difference of the substituent group of the auxiliary Schiff base ligand in which the N3 - ion acts as an end-to-end bridge, while complex 3 is only a mononuclear complex with the N3 - ion as a terminal ligand due to the change of the Schiff base ligand linked through hydrogen bonds into a two-dimensional supramolecular network. In 1 and 2 the μ1,3-bridging azide ion mainly mediates antiferromagnetic interaction between MnIII ions compared to other similar azide-bridged MnIII chains; however, 1 behaves as an antiferromagnet below 9.6 K, while 2 exhibits a hidden weak ferromagnet below 7.8 K with an unusual coercive field as large as 2.3 kOe. In comparison, 3 only displays simple weak antiferromagnetism between MnIII ions. Furthermore, the successful preparation of these three complexes enriched the azide-bridged manganese(III) complexes not only structurally but magnetically.

Complex 1. The magnetic properties of complex 1 are shown in Figure . Figure a shows the temperature dependence of magnetic susceptibility from 1.9 to 300 K at a 1 kOe field. On cooling, the χm value increases slowly to a maximum value of 0.021 cm3 mol-1 at ca. 42.0 K, and then it has a small decrease to 0.017 cm3mol-1 at ca. 13.0 K, indicating the presence of an antiferromagnetic (AF) coupling. The following little anomaly around 10.0 K may be caused by a long-range antiferromagnetic ordering, which will be proved by the subsequent magnetism measurements. With the temperature further cooling down below 10.0 K, the χm value shows a sharp decrease again possibly due to the effect of zero-field splitting (ZFS) arising from the MnIII ion, the antiferromagnetic interaction between chains, and/or a field saturation effect. The data above 150 K obey the Curie−Weiss law (χm = C/(T − θ)) with C = 3.04 cm3 mol-1 K and θ = −69.7 K. The Curie constant is close to 3.0 cm3 mol-1 K as expected for one uncoupled spin-only MnIII ion, while the negative θ value confirms the dominant AF coupling between MnIII ions. Although this is at very low temperatures where some anisotropy may be significant, MnIII is expected to be Heisenberg-like in its magnetic properties. Fitting the data above 13 K using the model given by Weng and modified by Hiller with H = −2JS Mn S Mn gives the best fit parameters J = −4.4 cm-1, zJ ‘ = −1.4 cm-1 (z = 4), g = 2.016, and R = 1.4 × 10-4 {R = ∑[(χm)obs - (χm)calcd]2/∑(χm)obs 2} in which J and zJ ‘ represent the intrachain and interchain coupling constants between MnIII centers, respectively. These values prove an obvious AF coupling between not only intrachain MnIII ions but also interchain MnIII centers.

Complex 2. The temperature dependence of the magnetic susceptibility of complex 2 was measured in 2.0−300 K with an applied field of 2 kOe, as shown in Figure a. On cooling, the χm value keeps smoothly increasing and shows a broad peak at about 30 K, which reveals an overall antiferromagnetic coupling between MnIII ions in 2. With further lowering temperature, the χm value exhibits an abrupt increase at around 13 K until it reaches a maximum of 0.22 cm3 mol-1 at 2.0 K, attributed to the weak ferromagnetism due to spin canting. The magnetic susceptibility above 100 K can be fit to the Curie−Weiss law; the Curie constant C value of 3.05 cm3 mol-1 K agrees very well with one independent high-spin MnIII ion, and the negative Weiss constant θ value of −51.1 K further confirms the strong antiferromagnetic coupling in 2. A similar method to 1 was used to deal with the data above 20 K with the Weng model and gives the best-fitting results:  J = −3.0 cm-1, zJ ‘ = −2.5 cm-1 (z = 4), g = 2.049, and R = 7.4 × 10-5. In contrast with 1, it seems that the intrachain coupling between MnIII ions in 2 is weaker while the interchain interaction is a bit stronger.

Complex 3. The magnetic property of complex 3 is relatively simple in contrast with those of 1 and 2, as shown in Figure S4 (Supporting Information). From χm T versus T and versus T plots (Figure S4a) the χm T value at room temperature is 3.00 cm3 mol-1 K, in good accordance with the theoretical value for one spin-only high-spin MnIII ion. Upon cooling, the values of χm T keep decreasing in the 300−1.9 K range, indicating an overall antiferromagnetic coupling in 3. The magnetic susceptibility above 10 K can be well fit to the Curie−Weiss law with C = 3.02 cm3 mol-1 K, θ = −1.9 K. The Curie constant C value is also close to the expected value of 3.0 cm3 mol-1 K for one noninteracting MnIII ion (S = 2, g = 2), and the small negative θ value further confirms a possible very weak antiferromagnetic interaction in 3. The M versus H plot measured at 2.0 K (Figure S4b) shows that magnetization increases smoothly and reaches 2.94 Nβ mol-1, a bit smaller than the theoretical saturation value 4.0 Nβ mol-1 for one spin-only MnIII ion, confirming the weak antiferromagnetic interaction between MnIII ions again. Considering the long Mn···Mn distances in the structure of 3, we fit the data in a range of 2−300 K with the spin-only susceptibility model for a single MnIII ion19 and obtained the following best results:  zJ ‘ = −0.27 cm-1, g = 2.028, and R = 6.9 × 10-4, which also show the weak antiferromagneic interaction between the MnIII ions linked through hydrogen bonds.
